Here’s the more detailed execution plan.

Step 1: Containerize the UI

Create a real Dockerfile for the UI app instead of relying on Docker Compose.

Goal:
Build the UI into static files, then serve it from a small web server container.
Inputs:
- UI source code
- package.json / lock file
- nginx.conf or equivalent web server config
Output:
- A runnable UI image

Test locally first:

docker build -t tasking-ui:local .
docker run --rm -p 8080:8080 tasking-ui:local

Then open:

http://localhost:8080

⸻

Step 2: Make CI deterministic

CI should not depend on someone’s laptop, Docker Compose, or manually installed tools.

Use fixed versions:

image: node:20

Run the same commands every time:

npm ci
npm run lint
npm test
npm run build

Avoid:

npm install

because it can change dependency versions.

CI should fail if:

- dependencies do not install cleanly
- lint fails
- tests fail
- the UI does not build
- the container image cannot build

⸻

Step 3: Build the container in GitLab CI

Add jobs like this:

stages:
  - validate
  - test
  - build
  - publish
validate:
  image: node:20
  stage: validate
  script:
    - npm ci
    - npm run lint
test:
  image: node:20
  stage: test
  script:
    - npm ci
    - npm test
build_ui:
  image: node:20
  stage: build
  script:
    - npm ci
    - npm run build

Then build the image:

build_container:
  stage: build
  image: docker:27
  services:
    - docker:27-dind
  script:
    - docker build -t "$CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHORT_SHA" .

⸻

Step 4: Publish image to GitLab registry

Only publish from approved branches.

publish_container:
  stage: publish
  image: docker:27
  services:
    - docker:27-dind
  script:
    - docker login -u "$CI_REGISTRY_USER" -p "$CI_REGISTRY_PASSWORD" "$CI_REGISTRY"
    - docker build -t "$CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHORT_SHA" .
    - docker push "$CI_REGISTRY_IMAGE:$CI_COMMIT_SHORT_SHA"
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "dev"'
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "release"'
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"'

That gives you image tags like:

registry.gitlab.com/group/tasking-ui:a1b2c3d

⸻

Step 5: Create a separate CD/manifest repo

This repo should not build the app. It should only deploy known images.

Example:

tasking-ui-manifests/
  dev/
    deployment.yaml
    service.yaml
    ingress.yaml
  staging/
    deployment.yaml
    service.yaml
    ingress.yaml
  prod/
    deployment.yaml
    service.yaml
    ingress.yaml
  .gitlab-ci.yml

Each environment can have different values:

dev:
- fewer replicas
- dev namespace
- dev URL
staging:
- staging namespace
- release candidate image
prod:
- manual approval
- high-side deployment rules

⸻

Step 6: Update Kubernetes deployment image

Example deployment.yaml:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: tasking-ui
  namespace: tasking-dev
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: tasking-ui
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: tasking-ui
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: tasking-ui
          image: registry.gitlab.com/group/tasking-ui:IMAGE_TAG
          ports:
            - containerPort: 8080

The CD pipeline replaces IMAGE_TAG with the actual commit SHA.

sed -i "s/IMAGE_TAG/$IMAGE_TAG/g" dev/deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f dev/

⸻

Step 7: CD branch rules

Use branch-to-environment mapping:

feature/*  → no deploy
dev        → deploy dev
release/*  → deploy staging
main       → manual prod deploy

Example:

deploy_dev:
  stage: deploy
  image: bitnami/kubectl:latest
  script:
    - kubectl config use-context "$DEV_CONTEXT"
    - sed -i "s/IMAGE_TAG/$IMAGE_TAG/g" dev/deployment.yaml
    - kubectl apply -f dev/
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "dev"'
deploy_prod:
  stage: deploy
  image: bitnami/kubectl:latest
  script:
    - kubectl config use-context "$PROD_CONTEXT"
    - sed -i "s/IMAGE_TAG/$IMAGE_TAG/g" prod/deployment.yaml
    - kubectl apply -f prod/
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"'
      when: manual

⸻

Step 8: Runner strategy

Use the shared runner for normal CI:

lint
unit tests
container build
image publish

Use environment-specific runners for deployments:

dev runner      → deploys to dev
staging runner  → deploys to staging
prod/high-side runner → deploys to prod/high-side

Reason:

CI can run anywhere trusted.
CD should run only where it has network access and credentials for that environment.

⸻

Step 9: Low-side vs high-side plan

Low-side/dev:

- normal GitLab registry
- shared runner okay
- automatic deploy to dev

High-side/prod:

- separate registry or promoted image import
- locked-down runner
- manual approval
- no automatic feature branch deploy
- deployment only from main or signed release tag

Recommended prod rule:

rules:
  - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"'
    when: manual

⸻

Step 10: Final pipeline flow

Developer pushes feature branch
        ↓
CI runs lint/test/build
        ↓
Merge to dev
        ↓
CI publishes container image
        ↓
CD deploys dev manifests
        ↓
Promote to release/staging
        ↓
CD deploys staging
        ↓
Merge/tag main
        ↓
Manual CD deploy to prod/high-side

The core idea: CI proves and packages the app. CD deploys an already-built image using environment-specific manifests.
